{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":32235,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"2f4dc940-f9a0-11e7-b606-797df35ec438","userId":null},"url":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/","params":{"0":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/"},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.73.222","x-forwarded-proto":"http","x-real-ip":"66.249.73.222","host":"bryanmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{},"query":{}},"res":{"_headers":{"x-powered-by":"Express","cache-control":"public, max-age=0","content-type":"text/html; charset=utf-8","etag":"W/\"62d9-97YT+OhFpDhf/qaMWRO1aXjtdFY\"","vary":"Accept-Encoding","content-encoding":"gzip"},"statusCode":200,"responseTime":"118ms"},"msg":"","time":"2018-01-15T03:00:04.300Z","v":0}
{"name":"Log","hostname":"localhost","pid":32235,"level":30,"req":{"meta":{"requestId":"f615d900-f9a0-11e7-b606-797df35ec438","userId":null},"url":"/","method":"GET","originalUrl":"/2017/12/28/wordpress-on-aws-part-2/amp/","params":{},"headers":{"x-forwarded-for":"66.249.73.222","x-forwarded-proto":"http","x-real-ip":"66.249.73.222","host":"bryanmonsalvatge.com","connection":"close","accept":"text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8","from":"googlebot(at)googlebot.com","user-agent":"Mozilla/5.0 (Linux; Android 6.0.1; Nexus 5X Build/MMB29P) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/41.0.2272.96 Mobile Safari/537.36 (compatible; Googlebot/2.1; +http://www.google.com/bot.html)","accept-encoding":"gzip,deflate,br"},"body":{"post":{"slug":"wordpress-on-aws-part-2","status":"published","id":"5a45becefd55d33f00065ac4","uuid":"b3202bc1-7869-4d4a-acd0-3a716a452042","title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 2","html":"<div class=\"kg-card-markdown\"><p>To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.</p>\n<hr>\n<h1 id=\"creatingtherdsinstance\">Creating the RDS Instance</h1>\n<p>Now that we got our web server, let's setup our db server.  First go to the RDS section of the AWS Console, then instances (on the left), then click that big blue &quot;Launch DB Instance&quot; button.</p>\n<p>We're going to select &quot;MariaDB Community Edition&quot; and on the next page we will select &quot;Dev/Test&quot; to remain in free and since we're learning.</p>\n<p>On the next page, check the box &quot;Only show options that are eligible for RDS Free Tier&quot; as that'll narrow down our select.  Once that's been checked, click the drop down next to DB Engine Version and select the latest version of MariaDB.   As seen below. in the settings section you will need to specify a DB instance identifier.  This identifier must be unique across all your RDS instances on your AWS account.  After we'll specify our DB user, I usually keep this root as we will specify a new user after for our WordPress site.  Make sure you save this password!.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.21.44-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.21.44-PM\"></p>\n<p>Next we'll specify our VPC environment for connectivity.  Make sure that it is on whatever VPC your EC2 instance is on.  We also do not want this DB publicly accessible.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.26.05-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.26.05-PM\"></p>\n<p>Now once that's setup, we're going to edit that security group we just created from the RDS setup wizard.  On the instance tab, click on your RDS instance and in the bottom pane, click the magnify glass icon from the left tab menu and then click on the security group as shown below:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.31.26-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.31.26-PM\"><br>\n<img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.30.17-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.30.17-PM\"></p>\n<p>We're going to go to the &quot;Inbound&quot; tab and hit edit, then add the following rule:</p>\n<p><img src=\"/content/images/2017/12/Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.32.37-PM.png\" alt=\"Screen-Shot-2017-10-02-at-11.32.37-PM\"></p>\n<p>The part highlighted is the GroupID for our WebDMZ security group.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>In a few minutes your RDS instance should finish intializing and you have successfully deployed your database service.  Next we will start logging into our Web instance that we setup in the first part.  From there we will configure our environment variables that we'll need in order to host a WordPress site.</p>\n</div>","feature_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Untitled-3-1.png","featured":false,"page":false,"locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":"WordPress on AWS - Part 2","meta_description":"To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.  For this tutorial we will be using MariaDB.","created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","published_at":{},"published_by":"1","custom_excerpt":"To pickup where we have left off, in part, we are going to begin the creation of our RDS instance.","codeinjection_head":"","codeinjection_foot":"","og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"custom_template":null,"tags":{"0":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaafe","name":"Wordpress","slug":"wordpress","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"1":{"id":"5a45c050fd55d33f00065ac5","name":"RDS","slug":"rds","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"2":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbab00","name":"aws","slug":"aws","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null},"3":{"id":"5a45b7a2e32546392fdbaaff","name":"tutorial","slug":"tutorial","description":null,"feature_image":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"created_at":{},"created_by":"1","updated_at":{},"updated_by":"1","parent":null}},"author":{"id":"1","name":"Bryan Monsalvatge","slug":"bryan","profile_image":"/content/images/2017/12/profilepic.jpg","cover_image":"/content/images/2017/12/Machine-Learning-in-the-Workplace_Blog-Banner-Image_1200x734px.png","bio":null,"website":null,"location":"Orlando","facebook":null,"twitter":"@BMonsalvatge","accessibility":"{\"nightShift\":true}","locale":null,"visibility":"public","meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"tour":"[\"getting-started\",\"using-the